Why is Accessibility Important?

02
On this page
  1. Accessibility as a Moral Case
  2. Accessibility as a Business Case
  3. Accessibility: The Legal Situation

Accessibility as a Moral Case

The moral case for accessibility has always been the most important to me.

Accessibility is necessary and the right thing to do.

Before the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) passed in 1990, activists organized an event called The Capitol Crawl. In this demonstration people got out of their wheelchairs and crawled up steps to show how a lack of physical access in public spaces impacts people with disabilities.

The impacts are echoed in the digital space when accessibility is not prioritized.

There have been times in my career where I felt that I was swimming upstream because my people-focused motivation didn’t really match the priorities set by the higher-ups in the organization.

If you find yourself in the same situation, it can be helpful to appeal to the business case for accessibility.

Accessibility as a Business Case

Numbers can be persuasive for stakeholders.

Here are some that may help you change some minds:

  • At least one billion people– 15% of the world’s population– have a recognized disability.
  • People with disabilities & the people in their lives control $8 trillion in spending.
  • The disposable income for working-age people with disabilities is $645 billion, and is comparable to other market segments like African Americans and Hispanic people.
  • There were 4,055 ADA-related lawsuits filed against businesses in the United States in 2021– a 15% increase from 2020.

While there are some questionable lawsuits that make up that number, it is important to note that legal action is rooted in people’s civil rights.

For more on the business case for accessibility, check out this resource from the W3C’s Web Accessibility Initiative (WAI).

Accessibility: The Legal Situation

Note: I am not a lawyer but a web developer who cares about accessibility. I get a lot of questions about the legal accessibility situation and it is important.

Depending on where your team is located, there will be different (or perhaps no) laws protecting digital civil rights to access.

In the United States, people with disabilities have protections through several laws including the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA), the Air Carrier Access Act (ACAA), and the Communications and Video Accessibility Act (CVAA).

Section 508 of the Rehabilitation Act in the United States requires that any software created or procured by the government is accessible.

The United States Department of Justice has issued guidance that enforcing website accessibility is a priority, but it is currently not an ADA requirement to follow the Web Accessibility Initiative’s WCAG standards.

Canada’s legislation includes the Accessible Canada Act and AODA. Jennifer Doyle from SiteImprove has written an article that provides an overview of Canada’s accessibility laws.

The European Union has enacted the Web Accessibility Directive that affects the public sector such as governments. The European Accessibility Act will include the private sector, although my understanding is that the implementation phase in member countries will run at least through 2025.

For more on the legal situation around accessibility, I recommend following Lainey Feingold.

Lainey is a disability rights attorney from California. For almost a decade she has maintained a guide to digital accessibility laws around the globe. She also presented a talk the 2022 CSUN conference that I highly recommend, as well as her book Structured Negotiation.
